          "body": "Verse 7 is the chapter’s most-quoted line: *Each one must do just as he has purposed in his heart, not grudgingly or under compulsion, for God loves a cheerful giver*. The Greek *hilaros* (only here in the NT) supplies the English *hilarious* — joyful, glad, eager. Paul disqualifies two postures: *lupe* (grief, regret) and *anagke* (compulsion, force). What God *loves* is the gift offered with delight. Verse 8 then supplies the resource that makes such giving possible: *God is able (dunatei) to make all grace abound to you, so that always having all sufficiency in everything, you may have an abundance for every good deed.* The vocabulary is hyperbolic on purpose — *all* grace, *always*, *all* sufficiency, *in everything*, *abundance*, *every* good deed. The believer’s capacity to give cheerfully rests on God’s capacity to supply abundantly. Scarcity-thinking is the enemy of generosity; abundance-trust is its engine."
