          "title": "The doxological climax (vv. 12-15)",
          "body": "The chapter’s final movement reveals what giving *actually accomplishes*. The *ministry of this service* (v. 12 — *diakonia tes leitourgias*, priestly-cultic language) does two things: it *fully supplies the needs of the saints* (horizontal) AND *overflows through many thanksgivings to God* (vertical). The Corinthian offering produces, in Jerusalem, glorification of God for two things: *your obedience to your confession of the gospel of Christ* and *the liberality of your contribution* (v. 13). Generosity is *proof* (*dokime*) that the gospel-confession is real. The Jerusalem saints respond with *prayer* and *yearning affection* (v. 14) toward the Corinthians — the offering binds the body across cities. Then Paul breaks into doxology: *Thanks be to God for His indescribable gift!* (v. 15). The *anekdiegetos* (untellable) gift is almost certainly Christ Himself — the Father’s unspeakable gift, behind which every other gift is a small echo. The chapter that began with logistics ends in worship."
